english:
  title: On a Night Journey Through the Black Forest at Muryeong Station
  author: An Chim
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Darkness upon darkness—the forest turns black.
    Silent and lonely—a thousand trees cry out.
    The rain god first urges his horses forward,
    while the wind god suddenly furls his banner away.
    We gallop frantically, searching the sandy ridge,
    then urgently knock upon the rustic door.
    The horse grows weary, the traveler falls ill,
    and the dog's bark startles the sleeping master.
    Three rooms with crumbling walls,
    a single span of cold lamplight by the window.
    Sitting here, sleep will not come,
    when suddenly the morning sun rises in the east.
  footnotes:
    - Muryeong Station (武靈站) was a waystation along a major road route during the Joseon period. The title indicates this poem follows a rhyme scheme set by another poem about the same location.
    - The rain god and wind god are personifications from classical Chinese cosmology, adding mythic weight to the natural elements of the storm.
    - The 'three rooms with crumbling walls' suggests a humble, barely adequate shelter for the weary traveler.
